Divvy (Chicago, IL) Bike Share Exploration¶

Dataset (2018 - 2019)¶

by Raad AlHamdan¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Divvy is a bicycle sharing system in the City of Chicago and two adjacent suburbs operated by Lyft for the Chicago Department of Transportation. As of July 2019, it operated 5800 bicycles at 608 stations, covering almost all of the city. The datasets were obtained from https://www.divvybikes.com/system-data for the years 2018 and 2019, they were unzipped and placed in my local BikeTripData directory.

def my_describe(df):
    print('='*40)
    print('We have', df.shape[0], 'rows, and', df.shape[1], 'columns.')
    print('='*40)
    desc = df.describe([], include='all', datetime_is_numeric=True).T.replace(np.nan,'-')
    desc['type'] = df.dtypes.astype('str')
    desc['count'] = desc['count'].astype('int')
    if len(df.select_dtypes('number').columns):
        desc = desc[['type', 'count', 'unique', 'top', 'freq', 'mean', 'std', 'min', '50%', 'max']]
    else:
        desc = desc[['type', 'count', 'unique', 'top', 'freq']]
    return desc.sort_values(['type', 'count'])

In [6]:
### change data types ###
df['start_time'] = df['start_time'].astype('datetime64')
df['birthyear'] = df['birthyear'].astype('int16')
df['tripduration'] = df['tripduration'].str.replace(',', '').astype('float64')/60 # in minutes

### add time related columns ###
df['year'] = df['start_time'].dt.year
df['month'] = df['start_time'].dt.month
df['month_name'] = df['start_time'].dt.month
df['day_num'] = df['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df['day_of_week'] = df['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df['hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour

### drop end time ###
del df['end_time']

### fix days of week ###
days = {0:'Mon', 1:'Tue', 2:'Wed', 3:'Thu', 4:'Fri', 5:'Sat', 6:'Sun'}
df['day_of_week'] = df['day_of_week'].apply(lambda x: days[x])
weekdays = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
df['day_of_week'] = pd.Categorical(df['day_of_week'], categories=weekdays, ordered=True)

### fix month names ###
months = {1:'Jan', 2:'Feb', 3:'Mar', 4:'Apr', 5:'May', 6:'Jun', 7:'Jul',
          8:'Aug', 9:'Sep', 10:'Oct', 11:'Nov', 12:'Dec'}
df['month_name'] = df['month_name'].apply(lambda x: months[x])
month_ord = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun',
             'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
df['month_name'] = pd.Categorical(df['month_name'], categories=month_ord, ordered=True)

### add season ###
season = ['Winter','Spring','Summer','Fall']
seasons = dict(zip(range(1,13),
                   [season[(mon%12+3)//3-1] for mon in range(1,13)]))
df['season'] = df['month'].apply(lambda x: seasons[x]).astype('category')

### add age and age groups ###
df['age'] = 2019 - df['birthyear']
df = df[df['age'] >= 14]
df = df[df['age'] <= 80]
df['age_group'] = pd.cut(x=df['age'], bins=[0, 29, 39, 49, 59, np.inf],
                         labels=['<29', '30s', '40s', '50s', '60+'])

Now I will add some station location data to enrich my analysis...

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset was originally 7,421,094 rows, and 12 columns. After removing 1,151,908 rows that contain nulls and headers, then removing ages, trip-durations, and speeds that don't seem realistic, it was reduced by 15.52%. However, we still have a dataset with 6,269,186 rows and 28 columns, out of which 48.27% are from 2018 and 51.73% from 2019.

In addition, I have added year, month, month_name, day_num, day_of_week, hour, season, age, and age_group columns to enrich the analysis. Also added some location data to add suburb information and to create str_dist (distance between two stations) and speed.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I find the tripduration variable the most promising feature to study. But I will also examine distance and speed as main features.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

All other original and added features will be used against the interest features to find patterns and/or insights into the data.

Univariate Exploration¶

We will try first to know our dataset closely by looking at some of the variables...

The dataset tells us that we typically have a male ridership (74%) and subscriber user type (93%). Looking at age groups, naturally younger riders do the most rides, with people in their 30s riding a bit more than those in their 20s or less, the rest of the age groups come next at a decreasing count. Lastly, weather does seem to affect ridership counts, most rides are in warmer weather while least are when it's cold. We will look next at the distribution of the variable tripduration...

This count bar plot shows the frequency of trips between bike stations. I was interested in the different behaviors of subscribers and customers in terms of one way trips and round trips to the same station. The first graph shows that for subscribers the most popular bike path is from Canal St & Adams St to Michigan Ave & Washington St, while the most popular round trip station is Streeter Dr & Grand Ave. As for customers, the most popular bike path is Lake Shore Dr & Monroe St to Streeter Dr & Grand Ave, while the most popular round trip station is also Streeter Dr & Grand Ave. It is obvious that the one way trips taken by subscribers is much more than any other round or one way trips by almost triple.

df_temp = df_temp.pivot_table(index='suburb_from', columns='suburb_to', fill_value=np.nan)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,10))

ax.set_title('Suburb Origin-Destination Heatmap', fontdict={'fontsize':16}, pad=20)
ax.set_xlabel('Destination', fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel('Origin', fontsize=14);

# adapted from github/Geometrein

This heat-map shows the frequency of suburb origin and destination. On its diagonal, it shows the trips taken within the suburb, and the rest is in between suburbs. The darker the square the more rides as shown on the scale on the right. The blank squares represent NaNs.

If we take same suburb activity for example, we can see some suburbs enjoy high rides activity, such as Douglas, Hyde Park, Loop, Near North Side to name a few. As for the in between suburbs rides activity the highest is between Near West Side and Loop in either direction.

The Correlation Heatmap shown above is fairly straight forward, it reveals relationships between the numeric variables in our dataset with assigned colors, the hotter the colors show positive relation, while colder colors show negative relation. We can ignore the relationships of latitudes and longitudes as they signify only that we are in the same area (Chicago), and we can ignore the speed and str_dist correlation because one is calculated from the other. However, the str_dist and tripduration correlation is a positive and strong (0.85) and the two variables are independent of each other. I plan to investigate this further in the next cell...

df_temp = df[(df['tripduration'] <= 120) & (df['str_dist'] > 0)] # .sample(1_000_000)
df_temp.rename(columns={'str_dist':'Distance (km)','tripduration':'Trip Duration (min)'}, inplace=True)

x = df_temp['Distance (km)']
y = df_temp['Trip Duration (min)']

g = sns.jointplot(x=x, y=y, data=df_temp, height=10, kind='hex', color='lightgreen',
                  joint_kws={'gridsize':50,'bins':'log','color':'lightblue'})

g.fig.suptitle('Hexplot and Regression showing Correlation between Duration and Distance', fontsize=15)

g = sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, ax=g.ax_joint, line_kws={'color':'r'}, scatter_kws={'s':0.5, 'alpha':0.02})

g.set(ylim=(-2, 122));

Following up from the last graph... Hexplot is one way of exploring and visualizing a bivariate correlation, especially when handling a large datasets, because it splits the plotting window into several hexbins and then the number of observations which fall into each bin corresponds with a color to indicate density, darker color hexbin means that there are more observations or density, within that region. The observation frequency bar graphs can be seen along the spines as an additional reference for information. I used the hexplot to analyze how Trip Duration is related to Distance. We see the darkest hexbins in the bottom left, as it is the most dense because the majority of riders take trips less than 30 minutes and go less than 7 kilometers. As we increase hexbins the color slowly begins to fade. The regression line also confirms the relationship which indicates that there is an increasing positive relationship between the two variables. Lastly, I also plotted the scatter plot of the two variable with low alpha and small size to see if they would pile up and intensify the color and density, which they did in blue.
